BOTULISM, MARINATED MUSHROOMS - KAZAKHSTAN: (SOUTH KAZAKHSTAN PROVINCE)
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 19 Jan 2009
Source: Kazinform [in Russian, trans. Mod.NR, edited]
<http://www.inform.kz/showarticle.php?lang=rus&id=225846>


According to data from Ministry of Emergency Situations, 2 women that
were residing in South Kazakhstan province, in a village called
Tyulkubas, died as a result of botulism. According to the province's
Sanitary Epidemiological Surveillance centre, on 6 Jan 2009, 4
residents of Tyulkubas village were hospitalized with a diagnosis of
botulism. Out of the 4, 2 women died on 11 and 16 Jan 2009. The other
patients are in satisfactory condition.

According to the doctors, the patients could have been poisoned by
marinated mushrooms. Laboratory samples for analysis were taken from
all patients and all had anti-botulism serum injected.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-RUS
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Botulism is not uncommon in southern Kazakhstan. The highest
incidence was registered in 2005 and 2006, with cases of lethal
outcomes. In 2005 there were 72 cases of botulism and in 2006 there
were 31 cases of botulism registered. - Corr.BA

A map of Kazakhstan showing South Kazakhstan province can be found at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/kazakhst.pdf>. - Mod.LL

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Kazakhstan is available
at <http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=1517880&v=48.483,64.283,5>. - CopyEd.MJ]
